While in the Netherlands last month, I had the pleasure to visit dyer Sylvia @wolmetverve at her studio.

Sylvia and her assistant Pia @miss_zepia graciously let me into their work space and I was able to watch the whole process from prepping the yarn and dye, to getting colorful yarns ready for shipment.

What struck me is that it’s a lot of physical labor, back breaking actually. All that lifting of the pans filled with water and yarn, the rinsing, the lifting of all the skeins.

Not to mention the precise calculations of the dyes and formulas.

After the dye process, comes prepping of the website, taking pictures, getting the yarn ready for sale, prepping packages for shipment.

It is always good to see what’s happening at the back end, I have a lot of respect for dyers and all the work it involves to be a yarn dyeing business.

Of course I tried my hand on dyeing myself, it’s fun to try but I don’t think dyeing is my thing. I leave that up to the yarn dyeing professionals! 🎨

Thank you Sylvia and Pia for showing me what it means to be in the dye studio! Much respect! 👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼

Define yourself as a maker/crafter.
⠀
I am a crafter/maker who is passionate, thorough and fearless. I persevere, do research and show Self Leadership.
⠀
If I don’t know a certain technique, I do research. Once, I didn’t know K2tog, ssk, the mattress stitch and what have you. Instead of crying about it or throwing a fit, I GOOGLED IT and found answers on YOUTUBE.
⠀
I walk the whole journey myself from casting on, knitting AND finishing which includes seaming and weaving in the ends. It’s all part of the process.
⠀
Without any qualms or mercy, I will rip out if things go awry. Ripping must be done if you are not happy with the project or if you made a mistake. I don’t ever cry about ripping.
⠀
I don’t blame my tools, material or people around me if things are not going smoothly. I don’t tend to assume the victim role. Instead, I look at what I can do and change to improve and ensure my maker journey.
⠀
I have always sought out good teachers and respect their knowledge and time. Because of them, my knowledge and know-how have grown immensely.
⠀
I actually finish projects. I focus, get to work and get stuff done.
⠀
I loooove my medium of yarn/fiber and enjoy the whole process with its ups and downs.

Lastly, I loooove adorning myself with my own handmade items. I feel awesome and beautiful wearing my colorful handmade wardrobe! 
⠀
Your turn now: How would you define yourself as a maker/crafter?

This one is for designers out there who can’t see their own worth.
⠀
Several years ago, I wrote the “Put a Pom on it Hat”.
⠀
When I finished it, I said to myself: “This pattern is nothing special, nobody’s going to want it. Let me put it out for free.”
⠀
This was a mistake on my part. I didn’t see my own worth.
⠀
Once I put it out, I was contacted by several yarn store owners asking if they could use my pattern to sell hat kits and I agreed flabbergastedly. After all, I viewed my own work less than.
⠀
Many hat kits were sold, meaning a lot of money was made.
⠀
So, after all, my pattern was worth a whole lot.
⠀
Here’s my message to you: don’t devalue nor underestimate your worth.
⠀
A pattern is a vehicle to sell yarn.
A pattern is also a vehicle to give joy to many knitters.
⠀
Because without a pattern, most knitters don’t know where to begin or what to do.
⠀
Do you now see the value of your work?
Do you now see what effect your pattern has?
⠀
Until this day, my Put a Pom on it Hat remains available for free. It is a lesson to myself to never ever again underestimate my own worth.
⠀
And every time another Put a Pom on it hat kit is sold, I think to myself: “Damn, I could’ve gotten a cut so I can pay some damn bills.”

I know I needed valuable advice from the experts and this is what they told me:
⠀
🧶 Find a pattern you like.
🧶 Make sure you buy the right weight of yarn as described in the pattern.
⠀
🧶 Make. Your. Gauge. Swatch!
🧶 Wash. Your. Gauge. Swatch!
⠀
🧶 Measure your gauge swatch and if you are not on gauge, swatch again with different needles and measure again.
⠀
🧶 You must be on gauge!
⠀
I listened to the advice given to me by the experts and did EXACTLY what they told me to do.
⠀
And this is the result: a gorgeous sweater that fits me. My first sweater, y’all.

I don’t allow negative self talk.
⠀
I’m very aware of how I talk to myself and I carefully choose my words.
⠀
As a new knitter I could have easily said to myself:
⠀
😩 I could never knit a sweater, it’s too hard for me.
⠀
😩 I know I will fail because I just started knitting only a year ago.
⠀
😩 I know I will fail because I don’t know how to read a pattern.
⠀
😫 I’m afraid to make mistakes. I’ll mess everything up.
⠀
Talking negatively like that to yourself will bring you down and will get you no where.
⠀
Instead I would say to myself:
⠀
💃🏻 I don’t know how to knit a sweater but I’m going to learn and I’m up for the challenge.
⠀
💃🏻 I know I will conquer knitting a sweater even though I am a newbie knitter.
⠀
💃🏻 I will conquer reading a pattern and if I don’t understand something I can ask for help.
⠀
💃🏻 I know I will make mistakes and that’s totally okay. I fully allow myself to make mistakes. Making mistakes is how you learn to get better.
⠀
Talking positively to yourself is blessing yourself and will instill trust and belief in yourself.
⠀
The way you talk to yourself becomes a self fulfilling prophecy. Choose your words carefully!
⠀

When I was given an opportunity to submit three pieces to the Vogue Knitting Kaleidoscope Fashion Show in 2020, my very first reaction was “NO”.
⠀
The story I would tell myself was this:
⠀
“My designs don’t deserve to be featured in a fashion show because my style is too simple. My pieces are not elaborate nor spectacular… They’re just straight up simple straight lines, who is going to want to see that?”
⠀
Up until recently I still tell myself this story. Many of my designs have never been published because I don’t believe anybody is going to want to make them because it’s too simple.
⠀
Today I’m re-writing my story…
⠀
Simple, straight lines and not elaborate IS what I am.
⠀
Simple, straight lines and no drama IS the name of my game.
⠀
So instead of feeling a certain kind of way about it like not being good enough, I’m going to embrace my “simple” design sense and bring it to front and center of my work.
⠀
Instead of feeling ashamed about it (who is going to want this boring thing, they all going to laugh at me), I’m now going to fully embrace it and own it.
⠀
Simple, straight lines IS my strength and not my weakness.
⠀
Looking back, I’m happy that despite my feelings of not being good enough, and not being “elaborate” enough, I had the courage to say YES.
⠀
The result was that three of my very simple pieces were part of the Vogue Knitting Live Kaleidoscope Fashion Show in January 2020.

Shout out to all three models that walked my pieces.

But a very special shout out to the 2nd model walking on the runway, my all time muse Ms LiLi Washington @yblimited_official with who I connect with on a deep soul level.

You worked for weeks and weeks on a project and it didn’t come out right. Frog it.

⠀

⠀

⠀
Allow yourself to be disappointed. Even cry a little if you want to. But don’t linger in that space.
⠀
You now are given the opportunity to start anew.
You are able to take everything out, and start anew.
⠀
You no longer have to look at your disappointment because you created a new opportunity to make something else.
⠀
Where it all comes down to for me is this:
⠀
If it doesn’t please you, frog it. Periodt.

Nurse Nacho been taking good care of me and my husband @sundaysfromharlem who has been studying to become an Occupational Therapy Assistant has been pouring all his knowledge and care over his first patient, me.

But has there been knitting/crochet/pattern writing/spinning you may wonder?

Absolutely none.

Instead I have been ravenously reading books, watching business  course videos, making notes, writing in my journals, revisiting my shadow work assignments and integrating/processing what needed to come into my mind, being and spirit.

I found myself ploughing through Eckhart Tolle’s The Power of Now, only to toss it in a corner. Sorry, Eckhart, I just can’t, your writing is not for me.

Next I devoured The Big Leap by Gay Hendricks, YESSS to operating from my zone of genius!!! If only I had the damn guts to make the big leap to my next level… 
I highly recommend this book.

And now I’m starting The Artist’s Way by Julia Cameron.

How is it that I can never ease into something? I always am so gung ho with absorbing anything.

I blame this obsessive gung ho behavior on my Dad and realize I am so much like him as I get older.

Happy Birthday, Dad…

My physical appearance gives it away: I am undeniably Asian.

I wasn’t born in Asia, nor have I ever lived in Asia.

I have never given being Asian much thought, nor have I ever celebrated that I am Asian.

Although my race is easily classified, my ethnicity is not.

Chinese? Filipino? Japanese? Thai? Korean? 

I tell you what I am:

I am a lover of yarn, maker of beautiful items.
I am a knitter, crocheter, spinner, weaver.
I am a pattern writer, architect of knitted garments.
I am adventurous, curious, passionate about my craft, always up to learning something new.

I am Javanese, yet born in Suriname and raised in the Netherlands, now living in the United States of America.

I have finally arrived at a place where I embrace all of my cultural identities. And where I no longer worry about how the outside world views me, classifies me or places pre-conceived notions and attributes to my physical appearance.
